    "post_id": 4,
    "title": "Lizards in Southwest Native American Culture",
    "slug": "lizards-in-southwest-native-american-culture",
    "author": "Alyssa Lu",
    "date": "2024-08-20",
    "thumbnail": "https://drive.google.com/thumbnail?id=1Nn-N2NUWUvSb7cEo-D7fcHCBOiq8xkjF",
    "tags": [
      "native american",
      "southwest",
      "culture",
      "navajo",
      "lizards",
      "gila monster"
    ],
    "summary": "For many Native Southwest tribes, lizards and their kin, like the Horned Toad and Gila Monster, hold deep spiritual value, symbolizing healing, protection, and survival.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "Lizards: More Than Backyard Accessories",
        "content": "<p>If you're ever taking a stroll on a dirt path in Phoenix at night, you can sometimes hear a faint twitchy scurrying sound around your footsteps. This is usually a lizard; one of the cold-blooded creatures who adore the Southwest heat.</p><p>While modern residents view them as simple backyard accessories, for the Navajo and other Native Southwest tribes, they have much more spiritual value.</p>",
        "image": {
          "source": "https://www.placeholderimage.online/placeholder/800/600/f3f4f6/1f2937?font=Lato.svg/seedpot-lizard-warriors.jpg",
          "caption": "A 2014-04 Seedpot with Lizard and Horned Toad Warriors Hunting Ants."
        }
      },
      {
        "heading": "Symbol of Healing and Rebirth",
        "content": "<p>In one story, Coyote encounters a group of lizards sledding down a rock. After the lizards revive Coyote following an accident, the animal gains recognition for its spiritual significance.</p><p>Being one of the rare land-bound animals that can **regenerate cartilage**, it's not a surprise that lizards represent **healing, survival, and rebirth**.</p>",
        "image": null
      },
      {
        "heading": "The Venomous Gila Monster",
        "content": "<p>The Gila Monster, which unlike most lizards is venomous, has stories about **resurrecting warriors** who fell in battle. Their powerful presence contributes to their spiritual standing within tribal narratives.</p>",
        "image": {
          "source": "https://www.placeholderimage.online/placeholder/800/600/f3f4f6/1f2937?font=Lato.svg/gila-monster-venomous.jpg",
          "caption": "A picture of a Gila Monster, known for its venom and its role in stories of resurrection."
        }
      },
      {
        "heading": "The Horned Toad: Grandfather of Protection",
        "content": "<p>One of the most important reptiles in Navajo culture is the Horned Toad, who is also called **Grandfather (Cheii)**. One Navajo story shows that when Lightning challenged Horned Toad, the toad averted the attacks each time using songs and eventually defeated Lightning with its spikes. Thus, his songs are used for **protection**.</p><p>Because of its array of spikes, the horned toad is a powerful symbol of protection—not only of one's physical body, but also one's mind, spirit, and emotions, due to its proximity to the ground.</p>",
        "image": {
          "source": "https://www.placeholderimage.online/placeholder/800/600/f3f4f6/1f2937?font=Lato.svg/horned-lizard-protection.jpg",
          "caption": "A picture of a Horned lizard, or 'Grandfather,' respected as a symbol of protection."
        }
      },
      {
        "heading": "The Finger Debate (Pomo Tribe)",
        "content": "<p>Though not in Arizona, the Pomo tribe tells another story about Lizard and Coyote, where the two had a throw down to decide whether humans should have fingers or paws, like Coyote. Thankfully, Lizard won, giving humans their dexterity.</p>",
        "image": null
      },
      {
        "heading": "Threats to a Sacred Population",
        "content": "<p>With temperatures in the Southwest rising, and Arizona's pesticides, population, and asphalt spreading, Gila monsters, lizards, and Horned toads have found their once bountiful population decreasing. The Horned lizards that old residents of Tucson and Catalina Foothills used to see out and about are 'essentially extinct in Phoenix, outside mountain parks'.</p><p>Even if we don't have much place for lizards in our rapidly expanding society, that does not mean we should not respect them. We should dread the night we walk outside and find that we suddenly can't seem to spot those familiar little twigs scurrying around in the crevices they used to.</p>",
        "image": null
      }
    ]
  },
